name: NOP
desc: Does nothing.

name: SWAP
desc: Same as `s1 XCHG0`.

name: XCHG_0I
desc: Interchanges `s0` with `s[i]`, `1 <= i <= 15`.

name: XCHG_IJ
desc: Interchanges `s[i]` with `s[j]`, `1 <= i < j <= 15`.

name: XCHG_0I_LONG
desc: Interchanges `s0` with `s[ii]`, `0 <= ii <= 255`.

name: XCHG_1I
desc: Interchanges `s1` with `s[i]`, `2 <= i <= 15`.

name: PUSH
desc: Pushes a copy of the old `s[i]` into the stack.

name: DUP
desc: Same as `s0 PUSH`.

name: OVER
desc: Same as `s1 PUSH`.

name: POP
desc: Pops the old `s0` value into the old `s[i]`.

name: DROP
desc: Same as `s0 POP`, discards the top-of-stack value.

name: NIP
desc: Same as `s1 POP`.

name: XCHG3
desc: Equivalent to `s2 s[i] XCHG` `s1 s[j] XCHG` `s[k] XCHG0`.
tvm_asm:
s1 = parse_stack_register_u4
s2 = parse_stack_register_u4;
s3 = parse_stack_register_u4     
     => 0x40 | s1, (s2 << 4) | s3

name: XCHG2
desc: Equivalent to `s1 s[i] XCHG` `s[j] XCHG0`.

name: XCPU
desc: Equivalent to `s[i] XCHG0` `s[j] PUSH`.

name: PUXC
desc: Equivalent to `s[i] PUSH` `SWAP` `s[j] XCHG0`.

name: PUSH2
desc: Equivalent to `s[i] PUSH` `s[j+1] PUSH`.

name: XCHG3_ALT
desc: Long form of `XCHG3`.

name: XC2PU
desc: Equivalent to `s[i] s[j] XCHG2` `s[k] PUSH`.

name: XCPUXC
desc: Equivalent to `s1 s[i] XCHG` `s[j] s[k-1] PUXC`.

name: XCPU2
desc: Equivalent to `s[i] XCHG0` `s[j] s[k] PUSH2`.

name: PUXC2
desc: Equivalent to `s[i] PUSH` `s2 XCHG0` `s[j] s[k] XCHG2`.

name: PUXCPU
desc: Equivalent to `s[i] s[j-1] PUXC` `s[k] PUSH`.

name: PU2XC
desc: Equivalent to `s[i] PUSH` `SWAP` `s[j] s[k-1] PUXC`.

name: PUSH3
desc: Equivalent to `s[i] PUSH` `s[j+1] s[k+1] PUSH2`.

name: BLKSWAP
desc:
Permutes two blocks `s[j+i+1] … s[j+1]` and `s[j] … s0`.
`0 <= i,j <= 15`
Equivalent to `[i+1] [j+1] REVERSE` `[j+1] 0 REVERSE` `[i+j+2] 0 REVERSE`.

name: ROT2
stack: a b c d e f - c d e f a b
desc: Rotates the three topmost pairs of stack entries.

name: ROLL
desc:
Rotates the top `i+1` stack entries.
Equivalent to `1 [i+1] BLKSWAP`.

name: ROLLREV
desc:
Rotates the top `i+1` stack entries in the other direction.
Equivalent to `[i+1] 1 BLKSWAP`.

name: PUSH_LONG
desc:
Pushes a copy of the old `s[ii]` into the stack.
`0 <= ii <= 255`

name: POP_LONG
desc:
Pops the old `s0` value into the old `s[ii]`.
`0 <= ii <= 255`

name: ROT
stack: a b c - b c a
desc: Equivalent to `1 2 BLKSWAP` or to `s2 s1 XCHG2`.

name: ROTREV
stack: a b c - c a b
desc: Equivalent to `2 1 BLKSWAP` or to `s2 s2 XCHG2`.

name: SWAP2
stack: a b c d - c d a b
desc: Equivalent to `2 2 BLKSWAP` or to `s3 s2 XCHG2`.

name: DROP2
desc: Equivalent to `DROP` `DROP`.

name: DUP2
stack: a b - a b a b
desc: Equivalent to `s1 s0 PUSH2`.

name: OVER2
stack: a b c d - a b c d a b
desc: Equivalent to `s3 s2 PUSH2`.

name: REVERSE
desc: Reverses the order of `s[j+i+1] … s[j]`.

name: BLKDROP
desc: Equivalent to `DROP` performed `i` times.

name: BLKPUSH
desc:
Equivalent to `PUSH s(j)` performed `i` times.
`1 <= i <= 15`, `0 <= j <= 15`.

name: PICK
desc: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then performs `s[i] PUSH`.

name: ROLLX
desc: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then performs `1 [i] BLKSWAP`.

name: -ROLLX
desc: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then performs `[i] 1 BLKSWAP`.

name: BLKSWX
desc: Pops integers `i`,`j` from the stack, then performs `[i] [j] BLKSWAP`.

name: REVX
desc: Pops integers `i`,`j` from the stack, then performs `[i] [j] REVERSE`.

name: DROPX
desc: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then performs `[i] BLKDROP`.

name: TUCK
desc: Equivalent to `SWAP` `OVER` or to `s1 s1 XCPU`.

name: XCHGX
desc: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then performs `s[i] XCHG`.

name: DEPTH
desc: Pushes the current depth of the stack.

name: CHKDEPTH
desc: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then checks whether there are at least `i` elements, generating a stack underflow exception otherwise.

name: ONLYTOPX
desc: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then removes all but the top `i` elements.

name: ONLYX
desc: Pops integer `i` from the stack, then leaves only the bottom `i` elements. Approximately equivalent to `DEPTH` `SWAP` `SUB` `DROPX`.

name: BLKDROP2
desc:
Drops `i` stack elements under the top `j` elements.
`1 <= i <= 15`, `0 <= j <= 15`
Equivalent to `[i+j] 0 REVERSE` `[i] BLKDROP` `[j] 0 REVERSE`.

name: NULL
desc: Pushes the only value of type _Null_.

name: ISNULL
desc: Checks whether `x` is a _Null_, and returns `-1` or `0` accordingly.

name: TUPLE
desc:
Creates a new _Tuple_ `t=(x_1, … ,x_n)` containing `n` values `x_1`,..., `x_n`.
`0 <= n <= 15`

name: NIL
desc: Pushes the only _Tuple_ `t=()` of length zero.

name: SINGLE
desc: Creates a singleton `t:=(x)`, i.e., a _Tuple_ of length one.

name: PAIR
desc: Creates pair `t:=(x,y)`.

name: TRIPLE
desc: Creates triple `t:=(x,y,z)`.

name: INDEX
desc:
Returns the `k`-th element of a _Tuple_ `t`.
`0 <= k <= 15`.

name: FIRST
desc: Returns the first element of a _Tuple_.

name: SECOND
desc: Returns the second element of a _Tuple_.

name: THIRD
desc: Returns the third element of a _Tuple_.

name: UNTUPLE
desc:
Unpacks a _Tuple_ `t=(x_1,...,x_n)` of length equal to `0 <= n <= 15`.
If `t` is not a _Tuple_, or if `|t| != n`, a type check exception is thrown.

name: UNSINGLE
desc: Unpacks a singleton `t=(x)`.

name: UNPAIR
desc: Unpacks a pair `t=(x,y)`.

name: UNTRIPLE
desc: Unpacks a triple `t=(x,y,z)`.

name: UNPACKFIRST
desc:
Unpacks first `0 <= k <= 15` elements of a _Tuple_ `t`.
If `|t|<k`, throws a type check exception.

name: CHKTUPLE
desc: Checks whether `t` is a _Tuple_. If not, throws a type check exception.

name: EXPLODE
desc: Unpacks a _Tuple_ `t=(x_1,...,x_m)` and returns its length `m`, but only if `m <= n <= 15`. Otherwise throws a type check exception.

name: SETINDEX
desc:
Computes _Tuple_ `t'` that differs from `t` only at position `t'_{k+1}`, which is set to `x`.
`0 <= k <= 15`
If `k >= |t|`, throws a range check exception.

name: SETFIRST
desc: Sets the first component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x` and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.

name: SETSECOND
desc: Sets the second component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x` and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.

name: SETTHIRD
desc: Sets the third component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x` and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.

name: INDEXQ
desc: Returns the `k`-th element of a _Tuple_ `t`, where `0 <= k <= 15`. In other words, returns `x_{k+1}` if `t=(x_1,...,x_n)`. If `k>=n`, or if `t` is _Null_, returns a _Null_ instead of `x`.

name: FIRSTQ
desc: Returns the first element of a _Tuple_.

name: SECONDQ
desc: Returns the second element of a _Tuple_.

name: THIRDQ
desc: Returns the third element of a _Tuple_.

name: SETINDEXQ
desc:
Sets the `k`-th component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x`, where `0 <= k < 16`, and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.
If `|t| <= k`, first extends the original _Tuple_ to length `n’=k+1` by setting all new components to _Null_. If the original value of `t` is _Null_, treats it as an empty _Tuple_. If `t` is not _Null_ or _Tuple_, throws an exception. If `x` is _Null_ and either `|t| <= k` or `t` is _Null_, then always returns `t'=t` (and does not consume tuple creation gas).

name: SETFIRSTQ
desc: Sets the first component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x` and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.

name: SETSECONDQ
desc: Sets the second component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x` and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.

name: SETTHIRDQ
desc: Sets the third component of _Tuple_ `t` to `x` and returns the resulting _Tuple_ `t'`.

name: TUPLEVAR
desc: Creates a new _Tuple_ `t` of length `n` similarly to `TUPLE`, but with `0 <= n <= 255` taken from the stack.

name: INDEXVAR
desc: Similar to `k INDEX`, but with `0 <= k <= 254` taken from the stack.

name: UNTUPLEVAR
desc: Similar to `n UNTUPLE`, but with `0 <= n <= 255` taken from the stack.

name: UNPACKFIRSTVAR
desc: Similar to `n UNPACKFIRST`, but with `0 <= n <= 255` taken from the stack.

name: EXPLODEVAR
desc: Similar to `n EXPLODE`, but with `0 <= n <= 255` taken from the stack.

name: SETINDEXVAR
desc: Similar to `k SETINDEX`, but with `0 <= k <= 254` taken from the stack.

name: INDEXVARQ
desc: Similar to `n INDEXQ`, but with `0 <= k <= 254` taken from the stack.

name: SETINDEXVARQ
desc: Similar to `k SETINDEXQ`, but with `0 <= k <= 254` taken from the stack.

name: TLEN
desc: Returns the length of a _Tuple_.

name: QTLEN
desc: Similar to `TLEN`, but returns `-1` if `t` is not a _Tuple_.

name: ISTUPLE
desc: Returns `-1` or `0` depending on whether `t` is a _Tuple_.

name: LAST
desc: Returns the last element of a non-empty _Tuple_ `t`.

name: TPUSH
desc: Appends a value `x` to a _Tuple_ `t=(x_1,...,x_n)`, but only if the resulting _Tuple_ `t'=(x_1,...,x_n,x)` is of length at most 255. Otherwise throws a type check exception.

name: TPOP
desc: Detaches the last element `x=x_n` from a non-empty _Tuple_ `t=(x_1,...,x_n)`, and returns both the resulting _Tuple_ `t'=(x_1,...,x_{n-1})` and the original last element `x`.

name: NULLSWAPIF
desc: Pushes a _Null_ under the topmost _Integer_ `x`, but only if `x!=0`.

name: NULLSWAPIFNOT
desc: Pushes a _Null_ under the topmost _Integer_ `x`, but only if `x=0`. May be used for stack alignment after quiet primitives such as `PLDUXQ`.

name: NULLROTRIF
stack: x y - x y or null x y
desc: Pushes a _Null_ under the second stack entry from the top, but only if the topmost _Integer_ `y` is non-zero.

name: NULLROTRIFNOT
stack: x y - x y or null x y
desc: Pushes a _Null_ under the second stack entry from the top, but only if the topmost _Integer_ `y` is zero. May be used for stack alignment after quiet primitives such as `LDUXQ`.

name: NULLSWAPIF2
stack: x - x or null null x
desc:
Pushes two nulls under the topmost _Integer_ `x`, but only if `x!=0`.
Equivalent to `NULLSWAPIF` `NULLSWAPIF`.

name: NULLSWAPIFNOT2
stack: x - x or null null x
desc:
Pushes two nulls under the topmost _Integer_ `x`, but only if `x=0`.
Equivalent to `NULLSWAPIFNOT` `NULLSWAPIFNOT`.

name: NULLROTRIF2
stack: x y - x y or null null x y
desc:
Pushes two nulls under the second stack entry from the top, but only if the topmost _Integer_ `y` is non-zero.
Equivalent to `NULLROTRIF` `NULLROTRIF`.

name: NULLROTRIFNOT2
stack: x y - x y or null null x y
desc:
Pushes two nulls under the second stack entry from the top, but only if the topmost _Integer_ `y` is zero.
Equivalent to `NULLROTRIFNOT` `NULLROTRIFNOT`.

name: INDEX2
desc:
Recovers `x=(t_{i+1})_{j+1}` for `0 <= i,j <= 3`.
Equivalent to `[i] INDEX` `[j] INDEX`.

name: CADR
desc: Recovers `x=(t_2)_1`.

name: CDDR
desc: Recovers `x=(t_2)_2`.

name: INDEX3
desc:
Recovers `x=t_{i+1}_{j+1}_{k+1}`.
`0 <= i,j,k <= 3`
Equivalent to `[i] [j] INDEX2` `[k] INDEX`.

name: CADDR
desc: Recovers `x=t_2_2_1`.

name: CDDDR
desc: Recovers `x=t_2_2_2`.

name: PUSHINT_4
desc:
Pushes integer `x` into the stack. `-5 <= x <= 10`.
Here `i` equals four lower-order bits of `x` (`i=x mod 16`).

name: ZERO
desc: Pushes a zero.

name: TEN
desc: Pushes a ten.

name: PUSHINT_8
desc: Pushes integer `xx`. `-128 <= xx <= 127`.

name: PUSHINT_16
desc: Pushes integer `xxxx`. `-2^15 <= xx < 2^15`.

name: PUSHINT_LONG
desc:
Pushes integer `xxx`.
_Details:_ 5-bit `0 <= l <= 30` determines the length `n=8l+19` of signed big-endian integer `xxx`.
The total length of this instruction is `l+4` bytes or `n+13=8l+32` bits.

name: PUSHPOW2
desc:
(Quietly) pushes `2^(xx+1)` for `0 <= xx <= 255`.
`2^256` is a `NaN`.

name: PUSHNAN
desc: Pushes a `NaN`.

name: PUSHREF
desc:
Pushes the reference `ref` into the stack.
_Details:_ Pushes the first reference of `cc.code` into the stack as a _Cell_ (and removes this reference from the current continuation).

name: PUSHREFSLICE
desc: Similar to `PUSHREF`, but converts the cell into a _Slice_.

name: PUSHREFCONT
desc: Similar to `PUSHREFSLICE`, but makes a simple ordinary _Continuation_ out of the cell.

name: PUSHSLICE
desc:
Pushes the slice `slice` into the stack.
_Details:_ Pushes the (prefix) subslice of `cc.code` consisting of its first `8x+4` bits and no references (i.e., essentially a bitstring), where `0 <= x <= 15`.
A completion tag is assumed, meaning that all trailing zeroes and the last binary one (if present) are removed from this bitstring.
If the original bitstring consists only of zeroes, an empty slice will be pushed.
Pushes an empty slice (bitstring ``).
Pushes bitstring `0`.
pushes bitstring `1`.

name: PUSHSLICE_REFS
desc:
Pushes the slice `slice` into the stack.
_Details:_ Pushes the (prefix) subslice of `cc.code` consisting of its first `1 <= r+1 <= 4` references and up to first `8xx+1` bits of data, with `0 <= xx <= 31`.
A completion tag is also assumed.
Is equivalent to `PUSHREFSLICE`.

name: PUSHSLICE_LONG
desc:
Pushes the slice `slice` into the stack.
_Details:_ Pushes the subslice of `cc.code` consisting of `0 <= r <= 4` references and up to `8xx+6` bits of data, with `0 <= xx <= 127`.
A completion tag is assumed.

fift_asm:
x{} PUSHSLICE
x{ABCD1234} PUSHSLICE
b{01101} PUSHSLICE
desc:
Examples of `PUSHSLICE`.
`x{}` is an empty slice. `x{...}` is a hexadecimal literal. `b{...}` is a binary literal.
More on slice literals [here](https://github.com/Piterden/TON-docs/blob/master/Fift.%20A%20Brief%20Introduction.md#user-content-51-slice-literals).
Note that the assembler can replace `PUSHSLICE` with `PUSHREFSLICE` in certain situations (e.g. if there’s not enough space in the current continuation).

fift_asm:
<b x{AB12} s, b> PUSHREF
<b x{AB12} s, b> PUSHREFSLICE
desc:
Examples of `PUSHREF` and `PUSHREFSLICE`.
More on building cells in fift [here](https://github.com/Piterden/TON-docs/blob/master/Fift.%20A%20Brief%20Introduction.md#user-content-52-builder-primitives).

name: PUSHCONT
tlb: #8F_ r:(## 2) xx:(## 7) c:(r * ^Cell) ssss:((8 * xx) * Bit)
desc:
Pushes a continuation made from `builder`.
_Details:_ Pushes the simple ordinary continuation `cccc` made from the first `0 <= r <= 3` references and the first `0 <= xx <= 127` bytes of `cc.code`.

name: PUSHCONT_SHORT
desc:
Pushes a continuation made from `builder`.
_Details:_ Pushes an `x`-byte continuation for `0 <= x <= 15`.

fift_asm:
<{ code }> PUSHCONT
<{ code }> CONT
CONT:<{ code }>
desc:
Pushes a continuation with code `code`.
Note that the assembler can replace `PUSHCONT` with `PUSHREFCONT` in certain situations (e.g. if there’s not enough space in the current continuation).

name: ADD
desc: Adds together two integers

name: SUBR
desc: Equivalent to `SWAP` `SUB`.

name: NEGATE
desc:
Equivalent to `-1 MULCONST` or to `ZERO SUBR`.
Notice that it triggers an integer overflow exception if `x=-2^256`.

name: INC
desc: Equivalent to `1 ADDCONST`.

name: DEC
desc: Equivalent to `-1 ADDCONST`.

name: DIV_BASE
tlb: #A9 m:uint1 s:uint2 cdft:(Either [ d:uint2 f:uint2 ] [ d:uint2 f:uint2 tt:uint8 ])
desc:
This is the general encoding of division, with an optional pre-multiplication and an optional replacement of the division or multiplication by a shift. Variable fields are as follows:
`0 <= m <= 1`  -  Indicates whether there is pre-multiplication (`MULDIV` and its variants), possibly replaced by a left shift.
`0 <= s <= 2`  -  Indicates whether either the multiplication or the division have been replaced by shifts: `s=0` - no replacement, `s=1` - division replaced by a right shift, `s=2` - multiplication replaced by a left shift (possible only for `m=1`).
`0 <= c <= 1`  -  Indicates whether there is a constant one-byte argument `tt` for the shift operator (if `s!=0`). For `s=0`, `c=0`. If `c=1`, then `0 <= tt <= 255`, and the shift is performed by `tt+1` bits. If `s!=0` and `c=0`, then the shift amount is provided to the instruction as a top-of-stack _Integer_ in range `0...256`.
`1 <= d <= 3`  -  Indicates which results of division are required: `1` - only the quotient, `2` - only the remainder, `3` - both.
`0 <= f <= 2`  -  Rounding mode: `0` - floor, `1` - nearest integer, `2` - ceiling.
All instructions below are variants of this.

name: DIV
desc: `q=floor(x/y)`, `r=x-y*q`

name: DIVR
desc: `q’=round(x/y)`, `r’=x-y*q’`

name: MOD
desc: where q=floor(x/y), r=x mod y=x-yq.

name: DIVMOD
desc: where q=floor(x/y), r=x-yq.

name: DIVMODR
desc: where q' = floor(x/y + 1/2), r' = x - yq'.

name: DIVMODC
desc: where q'' = ceil(x/y), r'' = x - yq''.

name: MULDIV
desc: `q=floor(x*y/z)`

name: MULDIVR
desc: `q'=round(x*y/z)`

name: MULDIVMOD
desc: `q=floor(x*y/z)`, `r=x*y-z*q`
Equivalent to `MULCONST 2` or to Forth's 2*.

name: POW2
desc:
`0 <= y <= 1023`
Equivalent to `ONE` `SWAP` `LSHIFT`.

name: AND
desc: Bitwise and of two signed integers `x` and `y`, sign-extended to infinity.

name: OR
desc: Bitwise or of two integers.

name: XOR
desc: Bitwise xor of two integers.

name: NOT
desc: Bitwise not of an integer.

name: FITS
desc:
Checks whether `x` is a `cc+1`-bit signed integer for `0 <= cc <= 255` (i.e., whether `-2^cc <= x < 2^cc`).
If not, either triggers an integer overflow exception, or replaces `x` with a `NaN` (quiet version).

name: CHKBOOL
desc: Checks whether `x` is a “boolean value'' (i.e., either 0 or -1).

name: UFITS
desc: Checks whether `x` is a `cc+1`-bit unsigned integer for `0 <= cc <= 255` (i.e., whether `0 <= x < 2^(cc+1)`).

name: CHKBIT
desc: Checks whether `x` is a binary digit (i.e., zero or one).

name: FITSX
desc: Checks whether `x` is a `c`-bit signed integer for `0 <= c <= 1023`.

name: UFITSX
desc: Checks whether `x` is a `c`-bit unsigned integer for `0 <= c <= 1023`.

name: BITSIZE
desc: Computes smallest `c >= 0` such that `x` fits into a `c`-bit signed integer (`-2^(c-1) <= c < 2^(c-1)`).

name: UBITSIZE
desc: Computes smallest `c >= 0` such that `x` fits into a `c`-bit unsigned integer (`0 <= x < 2^c`), or throws a range check exception.

name: MIN
desc: Computes the minimum of two integers `x` and `y`.

name: MAX
desc: Computes the maximum of two integers `x` and `y`.

name: MINMAX
stack: x y - x y or y x
desc: Sorts two integers. Quiet version of this operation returns two `NaN`s if any of the arguments are `NaN`s.

name: ABS
desc: Computes the absolute value of an integer `x`.

name: QUIET
desc: prefix, transforming any arithmetic operation into its "quiet" variant, indicated by prefixing a Q to its mnemonic. Such operations return NaNs instead of throwing integer overflow exceptions if the results do not fit in Integer's, or if one of their arguments is a NaN. Notice that this does not extend to shift amounts and other parameters that must be within a small range (e.g., 0-1023). Also notice that this does not disable type-checking exceptions if a value of a type other than Integer is supplied.

name: QADD
desc: Always works if x and y are Integers, but returns a NaN if the addition cannot be performed.

name: QDIV
desc: Division returns `NaN` if `y=0`.

name: QAND
desc: Bitwise and (similar to AND), but returns a NaN if either x or y is a NaN instead of throwing an integer overflow exception. However, if one of the arguments is zero, and the other is a NaN, the result is zero.

name: QOR
desc: Bitwise or. If x = -1 or y = -1, the result is always -1, even if the other argument is a NaN.

name: QFITS
desc: Replaces `x` with a `NaN` if x is not a `cc+1`-bit signed integer, leaves it intact otherwise.

name: QUFITS
desc: Replaces `x` with a `NaN` if x is not a `cc+1`-bit unsigned integer, leaves it intact otherwise.

name: QUFITS_8
desc: Checks whether x is an unsigned byte (i.e., whether 0 <= x < 2^8), and replaces x with a NaN if this is not the case; leaves x intact otherwise (i.e., if x is an unsigned byte).

name: QFITSX
desc: Replaces `x` with a `NaN` if x is not a c-bit signed integer, leaves it intact otherwise.

name: QUFITSX
desc: Replaces `x` with a `NaN` if x is not a c-bit unsigned integer, leaves it intact otherwise.

name: SGN
desc:
Computes the sign of an integer `x`:
`-1` if `x<0`, `0` if `x=0`, `1` if `x>0`.

name: LESS
desc: Returns `-1` if `x<y`, `0` otherwise.

name: EQUAL
desc: Returns `-1` if `x=y`, `0` otherwise.

name: NEQ
desc: Equivalent to `EQUAL` `NOT`.

name: GEQ
desc: Equivalent to `LESS` `NOT`.

name: CMP
desc:
Computes the sign of `x-y`:
`-1` if `x<y`, `0` if `x=y`, `1` if `x>y`.
No integer overflow can occur here unless `x` or `y` is a `NaN`.

name: EQINT
desc:
Returns `-1` if `x=yy`, `0` otherwise.
`-2^7 <= yy < 2^7`.

name: ISZERO
desc: Checks whether an integer is zero. Corresponds to Forth's `0=`.

name: LESSINT
desc:
Returns `-1` if `x<yy`, `0` otherwise.
`-2^7 <= yy < 2^7`.

name: ISNEG
desc: Checks whether an integer is negative. Corresponds to Forth's `0<`.

name: ISNPOS
desc: Checks whether an integer is non-positive.

name: GTINT
desc:
Returns `-1` if `x>yy`, `0` otherwise.
`-2^7 <= yy < 2^7`.

name: ISPOS
desc: Checks whether an integer is positive. Corresponds to Forth's `0>`.

name: ISNNEG
desc: Checks whether an integer is non-negative.

name: NEQINT
desc:
Returns `-1` if `x!=yy`, `0` otherwise.
`-2^7 <= yy < 2^7`.

name: ISNAN
desc: Checks whether `x` is a `NaN`.

name: CHKNAN
desc: Throws an arithmetic overflow exception if `x` is a `NaN`.

name: SEMPTY
desc: Checks whether a _Slice_ `s` is empty (i.e., contains no bits of data and no cell references).

name: SDEMPTY
desc: Checks whether _Slice_ `s` has no bits of data.

name: SREMPTY
desc: Checks whether _Slice_ `s` has no references.

name: SDFIRST
desc: Checks whether the first bit of _Slice_ `s` is a one.

name: SDLEXCMP
desc: Compares the data of `s` lexicographically with the data of `s'`, returning `-1`, 0, or 1 depending on the result.

name: SDEQ
desc: Checks whether the data parts of `s` and `s'` coincide, equivalent to `SDLEXCMP` `ISZERO`.

name: SDPFX
desc: Checks whether `s` is a prefix of `s'`.

name: SDPFXREV
desc: Checks whether `s'` is a prefix of `s`, equivalent to `SWAP` `SDPFX`.

name: SDPPFX
desc: Checks whether `s` is a proper prefix of `s'` (i.e., a prefix distinct from `s'`).

name: SDPPFXREV
desc: Checks whether `s'` is a proper prefix of `s`.

name: SDSFX
desc: Checks whether `s` is a suffix of `s'`.

name: SDSFXREV
desc: Checks whether `s'` is a suffix of `s`.

name: SDPSFX
desc: Checks whether `s` is a proper suffix of `s'`.

name: SDPSFXREV
desc: Checks whether `s'` is a proper suffix of `s`.

name: SDCNTLEAD0
desc: Returns the number of leading zeroes in `s`.

name: SDCNTLEAD1
desc: Returns the number of leading ones in `s`.

name: SDCNTTRAIL0
desc: Returns the number of trailing zeroes in `s`.

name: SDCNTTRAIL1
desc: Returns the number of trailing ones in `s`.

name: DIFF
desc: Calculates diff between first and second parameters and returns it as cell.

name: DIFF_PATCH
desc: Takes the first parameter as document, the second parameter as patch, received on DIFF command, applies patch and saves result document to cell.

name: ZIP
desc: Zip string to cell

name: UNZIP
desc: Unzip cell to string

name: DIFF_ZIP
desc: like `DIFF` but unzip parameters before operation and zip to cell after operation.

name: DIFF_PATCH_ZIP
desc: like `DIFF_PATCH` but unzip parameters before operation and zip to cell after operation.

name: DIFF_PATCH_Q
desc: quiet version of `DIFF_PATCH`

name: DIFF_PATCH_ZIPQ
desc: quiet version of `DIFF_PATCH_ZIP`

name: DIFF_PATCH_BINARY
desc: like `DIFF_PATCH` but takes and returns binary arrays instead of string.

name: DIFF_PATCH_BINARY_ZIP
desc: like `DIFF_PATCH_ZIP` but takes and returns binary arrays instead of string.

name: DIFF_PATCH_BINARYQ
desc: like `DIFF_PATCHQ` but takes and returns binary arrays instead of string.

name: DIFF_PATCH_BINARY_ZIPQ
desc: like `DIFF_PATCH_ZIPQ` but takes and returns binary arrays instead of string.

name: NEWC
desc: Creates a new empty _Builder_.

name: ENDC
desc: Converts a _Builder_ into an ordinary _Cell_.

name: STI
desc: Stores a signed `cc+1`-bit integer `x` into _Builder_ `b` for `0 <= cc <= 255`, throws a range check exception if `x` does not fit into `cc+1` bits.

name: STU
desc: Stores an unsigned `cc+1`-bit integer `x` into _Builder_ `b`. In all other respects it is similar to `STI`.

name: STREF
desc: Stores a reference to _Cell_ `c` into _Builder_ `b`.

name: STBREFR
desc: Equivalent to `ENDC` `SWAP` `STREF`.

name: STSLICE
desc: Stores _Slice_ `s` into _Builder_ `b`.

name: STIX
desc: Stores a signed `l`-bit integer `x` into `b` for `0 <= l <= 257`.

name: STUX
desc: Stores an unsigned `l`-bit integer `x` into `b` for `0 <= l <= 256`.

name: STIXR
desc: Similar to `STIX`, but with arguments in a different order.

name: STUXR
desc: Similar to `STUX`, but with arguments in a different order.

name: STIXQ
stack: x b l - x b f or b' 0
desc:
A quiet version of `STIX`. If there is no space in `b`, sets `b'=b` and `f=-1`.
If `x` does not fit into `l` bits, sets `b'=b` and `f=1`.
If the operation succeeds, `b'` is the new _Builder_ and `f=0`.
However, `0 <= l <= 257`, with a range check exception if this is not so.

name: STUXQ
stack: x b l - x b f or b' 0
desc: A quiet version of `STUX`.

name: STIXRQ
stack: b x l - b x f or b' 0
desc: A quiet version of `STIXR`.

name: STUXRQ
stack: b x l - b x f or b' 0
desc: A quiet version of `STUXR`.

name: STI_ALT
desc: A longer version of `[cc+1] STI`.

name: STU_ALT
desc: A longer version of `[cc+1] STU`.

name: STIR
desc: Equivalent to `SWAP` `[cc+1] STI`.

name: STUR
desc: Equivalent to `SWAP` `[cc+1] STU`.

name: STIQ
stack: x b - x b f or b' 0
desc: A quiet version of `STI`.

name: STUQ
stack: x b - x b f or b' 0
desc: A quiet version of `STU`.

name: STIRQ
stack: b x - b x f or b' 0
desc: A quiet version of `STIR`.

name: STURQ
stack: b x - b x f or b' 0
desc: A quiet version of `STUR`.

name: STREF_ALT
desc: A longer version of `STREF`.

name: STBREF
desc: Equivalent to `SWAP` `STBREFR`.

name: STSLICE_ALT
desc: A longer version of `STSLICE`.

name: STB
desc: Appends all data from _Builder_ `b'` to _Builder_ `b`.

name: STREFR
desc: Equivalent to `SWAP` `STREF`.

name: STBREFR_ALT
desc: A longer encoding of `STBREFR`.

name: STSLICER
desc: Equivalent to `SWAP` `STSLICE`.

name: STBR
desc:
Concatenates two builders.
Equivalent to `SWAP` `STB`.

name: STREFQ
stack: c b - c b -1 or b' 0
desc: Quiet version of `STREF`.

name: STBREFQ
stack: b' b - b' b -1 or b'' 0
desc: Quiet version of `STBREF`.

name: STSLICEQ
stack: s b - s b -1 or b' 0
desc: Quiet version of `STSLICE`.

name: STBQ
stack: b' b - b' b -1 or b'' 0
desc: Quiet version of `STB`.

name: STREFRQ
stack: b c - b c -1 or b' 0
desc: Quiet version of `STREFR`.

name: STBREFRQ
stack: b b' - b b' -1 or b'' 0
desc: Quiet version of `STBREFR`.

name: STSLICERQ
stack: b s - b s -1 or b'' 0
desc: Quiet version of `STSLICER`.

name: STBRQ
stack: b b' - b b' -1 or b'' 0
desc: Quiet version of `STBR`.

name: STREFCONST
desc: Equivalent to `PUSHREF` `STREFR`.

name: STREF2CONST
desc: Equivalent to `STREFCONST` `STREFCONST`.

name: ENDXC
desc:
If `x!=0`, creates a _special_ or _exotic_ cell from _Builder_ `b`.
The type of the exotic cell must be stored in the first 8 bits of `b`.
If `x=0`, it is equivalent to `ENDC`. Otherwise some validity checks on the data and references of `b` are performed before creating the exotic cell.

name: STILE4
desc: Stores a little-endian signed 32-bit integer.

name: STULE4
desc: Stores a little-endian unsigned 32-bit integer.

name: STILE8
desc: Stores a little-endian signed 64-bit integer.

name: STULE8
desc: Stores a little-endian unsigned 64-bit integer.

name: BDEPTH
desc: Returns the depth of _Builder_ `b`. If no cell references are stored in `b`, then `x=0`; otherwise `x` is one plus the maximum of depths of cells referred to from `b`.

name: BBITS
desc: Returns the number of data bits already stored in _Builder_ `b`.

name: BREFS
desc: Returns the number of cell references already stored in `b`.

name: BBITREFS
desc: Returns the numbers of both data bits and cell references in `b`.

name: BREMBITS
desc: Returns the number of data bits that can still be stored in `b`.

name: BREMREFS
desc: Returns the number of references that can still be stored in `b`.

name: BREMBITREFS
desc: Returns the numbers of both data bits and references that can still be stored in `b`.

name: BCHKBITS
desc: Checks whether `cc+1` bits can be stored into `b`, where `0 <= cc <= 255`.

name: BCHKBITS_VAR
desc: Checks whether `x` bits can be stored into `b`, `0 <= x <= 1023`. If there is no space for `x` more bits in `b`, or if `x` is not within the range `0...1023`, throws an exception.

name: BCHKREFS
desc: Checks whether `y` references can be stored into `b`, `0 <= y <= 7`.

name: BCHKBITREFS
desc: Checks whether `x` bits and `y` references can be stored into `b`, `0 <= x <= 1023`, `0 <= y <= 7`.

name: BCHKBITSQ
desc: Checks whether `cc+1` bits can be stored into `b`, where `0 <= cc <= 255`.

name: BCHKBITSQ_VAR
desc: Checks whether `x` bits can be stored into `b`, `0 <= x <= 1023`.

name: BCHKREFSQ
desc: Checks whether `y` references can be stored into `b`, `0 <= y <= 7`.

name: BCHKBITREFSQ
desc: Checks whether `x` bits and `y` references can be stored into `b`, `0 <= x <= 1023`, `0 <= y <= 7`.

name: STZEROES
desc: Stores `n` binary zeroes into _Builder_ `b`.

name: STONES
desc: Stores `n` binary ones into _Builder_ `b`.

name: STSAME
desc: Stores `n` binary `x`es (`0 <= x <= 1`) into _Builder_ `b`.

name: STCONT
desc: Stores Continuation `cont` into Builder `b`.

name: STSLICECONST
desc:
Stores a constant subslice `sss`.
_Details:_ `sss` consists of `0 <= x <= 3` references and up to `8y+2` data bits, with `0 <= y <= 7`. Completion bit is assumed.
Note that the assembler can replace `STSLICECONST` with `PUSHSLICE` `STSLICER` if the slice is too big.

name: STZERO
desc: Stores one binary zero.

name: STONE
desc: Stores one binary one.

name: CTOS
desc: Converts a _Cell_ into a _Slice_. Notice that `c` must be either an ordinary cell, or an exotic cell which is automatically _loaded_ to yield an ordinary cell `c'`, converted into a _Slice_ afterwards.

name: ENDS
desc: Removes a _Slice_ `s` from the stack, and throws an exception if it is not empty.

name: LDI
desc: Loads (i.e., parses) a signed `cc+1`-bit integer `x` from _Slice_ `s`, and returns the remainder of `s` as `s'`.

name: LDU
desc: Loads an unsigned `cc+1`-bit integer `x` from _Slice_ `s`.

name: LDREF
desc: Loads a cell reference `c` from `s`.

name: LDREFRTOS
desc: Equivalent to `LDREF` `SWAP` `CTOS`.

name: LDSLICE
desc: Cuts the next `cc+1` bits of `s` into a separate _Slice_ `s''`.

name: LDIX
desc: Loads a signed `l`-bit (`0 <= l <= 257`) integer `x` from _Slice_ `s`, and returns the remainder of `s` as `s'`.

name: LDUX
desc: Loads an unsigned `l`-bit integer `x` from (the first `l` bits of) `s`, with `0 <= l <= 256`.

name: PLDIX
desc: Preloads a signed `l`-bit integer from _Slice_ `s`, for `0 <= l <= 257`.

name: PLDUX
desc: Preloads an unsigned `l`-bit integer from `s`, for `0 <= l <= 256`.

name: LDIXQ
stack: s l - x s' -1 or s 0
desc: Quiet version of `LDIX`: loads a signed `l`-bit integer from `s` similarly to `LDIX`, but returns a success flag, equal to `-1` on success or to `0` on failure (if `s` does not have `l` bits), instead of throwing a cell underflow exception.

name: LDUXQ
stack: s l - x s' -1 or s 0
desc: Quiet version of `LDUX`.

name: PLDIXQ
desc: Quiet version of `PLDIX`.

name: PLDUXQ
desc: Quiet version of `PLDUX`.

name: LDI_ALT
desc: A longer encoding for `LDI`.

name: LDU_ALT
desc: A longer encoding for `LDU`.

name: PLDI
desc: Preloads a signed `cc+1`-bit integer from _Slice_ `s`.

name: PLDU
desc: Preloads an unsigned `cc+1`-bit integer from `s`.

name: LDIQ
desc: A quiet version of `LDI`.

name: LDUQ
desc: A quiet version of `LDU`.

name: PLDIQ
desc: A quiet version of `PLDI`.

name: PLDUQ
desc: A quiet version of `PLDU`.

name: PLDUZ
desc: Preloads the first `32(c+1)` bits of _Slice_ `s` into an unsigned integer `x`, for `0 <= c <= 7`. If `s` is shorter than necessary, missing bits are assumed to be zero. This operation is intended to be used along with `IFBITJMP` and similar instructions.

name: LDSLICEX
desc: Loads the first `0 <= l <= 1023` bits from _Slice_ `s` into a separate _Slice_ `s''`, returning the remainder of `s` as `s'`.

name: PLDSLICEX
desc: Returns the first `0 <= l <= 1023` bits of `s` as `s''`.

name: LDSLICEXQ
stack: s l - s'' s' -1 or s 0
desc: A quiet version of `LDSLICEX`.

name: PLDSLICEXQ
desc: A quiet version of `LDSLICEXQ`.

name: LDSLICE_ALT
desc: A longer encoding for `LDSLICE`.

name: PLDSLICE
desc: Returns the first `0 < cc+1 <= 256` bits of `s` as `s''`.

name: LDSLICEQ
desc: A quiet version of `LDSLICE`.

name: PLDSLICEQ
desc: A quiet version of `PLDSLICE`.

name: SDCUTFIRST
desc: Returns the first `0 <= l <= 1023` bits of `s`. It is equivalent to `PLDSLICEX`.

name: SDSKIPFIRST
desc: Returns all but the first `0 <= l <= 1023` bits of `s`. It is equivalent to `LDSLICEX` `NIP`.

name: SDCUTLAST
desc: Returns the last `0 <= l <= 1023` bits of `s`.

name: SDSKIPLAST
desc: Returns all but the last `0 <= l <= 1023` bits of `s`.

name: SDSUBSTR
desc: Returns `0 <= l' <= 1023` bits of `s` starting from offset `0 <= l <= 1023`, thus extracting a bit substring out of the data of `s`.

name: SDBEGINSX
desc: Checks whether `s` begins with (the data bits of) `s'`, and removes `s'` from `s` on success. On failure throws a cell deserialization exception. Primitive `SDPFXREV` can be considered a quiet version of `SDBEGINSX`.

name: SDBEGINSXQ
desc: A quiet version of `SDBEGINSX`.

name: SDBEGINS
desc: Checks whether `s` begins with constant bitstring `sss` of length `8x+3` (with continuation bit assumed), where `0 <= x <= 127`, and removes `sss` from `s` on success.

name: SDBEGINSQ
desc: A quiet version of `SDBEGINS`.

name: SCUTFIRST
desc: Returns the first `0 <= l <= 1023` bits and first `0 <= r <= 4` references of `s`.

name: SSKIPFIRST
desc: Returns all but the first `l` bits of `s` and `r` references of `s`.

name: SCUTLAST
desc: Returns the last `0 <= l <= 1023` data bits and last `0 <= r <= 4` references of `s`.

name: SSKIPLAST
desc: Returns all but the last `l` bits of `s` and `r` references of `s`.

name: SUBSLICE
stack: s l r l' r' - s'
desc: Returns `0 <= l' <= 1023` bits and `0 <= r' <= 4` references from _Slice_ `s`, after skipping the first `0 <= l <= 1023` bits and first `0 <= r <= 4` references.

name: SPLIT
desc: Splits the first `0 <= l <= 1023` data bits and first `0 <= r <= 4` references from `s` into `s'`, returning the remainder of `s` as `s''`.

name: SPLITQ
stack: s l r - s' s'' -1 or s 0
desc: A quiet version of `SPLIT`.

name: XCTOS
desc: Transforms an ordinary or exotic cell into a _Slice_, as if it were an ordinary cell. A flag is returned indicating whether `c` is exotic. If that be the case, its type can later be deserialized from the first eight bits of `s`.

name: XLOAD
desc: Loads an exotic cell `c` and returns an ordinary cell `c'`. If `c` is already ordinary, does nothing. If `c` cannot be loaded, throws an exception.

name: XLOADQ
desc: Loads an exotic cell `c` and returns an ordinary cell `c'`. If `c` is already ordinary, does nothing. If `c` cannot be loaded, returns 0.

name: SCHKBITS
desc: Checks whether there are at least `l` data bits in _Slice_ `s`. If this is not the case, throws a cell deserialisation (i.e., cell underflow) exception.

name: SCHKREFS
desc: Checks whether there are at least `r` references in _Slice_ `s`.

name: SCHKBITREFS
desc: Checks whether there are at least `l` data bits and `r` references in _Slice_ `s`.

name: SCHKBITSQ
desc: Checks whether there are at least `l` data bits in _Slice_ `s`.

name: SCHKREFSQ
desc: Checks whether there are at least `r` references in _Slice_ `s`.

name: SCHKBITREFSQ
desc: Checks whether there are at least `l` data bits and `r` references in _Slice_ `s`.

name: PLDREFVAR
desc: Returns the `n`-th cell reference of _Slice_ `s` for `0 <= n <= 3`.

name: SBITS
desc: Returns the number of data bits in _Slice_ `s`.

name: SREFS
desc: Returns the number of references in _Slice_ `s`.

name: SBITREFS
desc: Returns both the number of data bits and the number of references in `s`.

name: PLDREFIDX
desc: Returns the `n`-th cell reference of _Slice_ `s`, where `0 <= n <= 3`.

name: PLDREF
desc: Preloads the first cell reference of a _Slice_.

name: LDILE4
desc: Loads a little-endian signed 32-bit integer.

name: LDULE4
desc: Loads a little-endian unsigned 32-bit integer.

name: LDILE8
desc: Loads a little-endian signed 64-bit integer.

name: LDULE8
desc: Loads a little-endian unsigned 64-bit integer.

name: PLDILE4
desc: Preloads a little-endian signed 32-bit integer.

name: PLDULE4
desc: Preloads a little-endian unsigned 32-bit integer.

name: PLDILE8
desc: Preloads a little-endian signed 64-bit integer.

name: PLDULE8
desc: Preloads a little-endian unsigned 64-bit integer.

name: LDILE4Q
desc: Quietly loads a little-endian signed 32-bit integer.

name: LDULE4Q
desc: Quietly loads a little-endian unsigned 32-bit integer.

name: LDILE8Q
desc: Quietly loads a little-endian signed 64-bit integer.

name: LDULE8Q
desc: Quietly loads a little-endian unsigned 64-bit integer.

name: PLDILE4Q
desc: Quietly preloads a little-endian signed 32-bit integer.

name: PLDULE4Q
desc: Quietly preloads a little-endian unsigned 32-bit integer.

name: PLDILE8Q
desc: Quietly preloads a little-endian signed 64-bit integer.

name: PLDULE8Q
desc: Quietly preloads a little-endian unsigned 64-bit integer.

name: LDZEROES
desc: Returns the count `n` of leading zero bits in `s`, and removes these bits from `s`.

name: LDONES
desc: Returns the count `n` of leading one bits in `s`, and removes these bits from `s`.

name: LDSAME
desc: Returns the count `n` of leading bits equal to `0 <= x <= 1` in `s`, and removes these bits from `s`.

name: SDEPTH
desc: Returns the depth of _Slice_ `s`. If `s` has no references, then `x=0`; otherwise `x` is one plus the maximum of depths of cells referred to from `s`.

name: CDEPTH
desc: Returns the depth of _Cell_ `c`. If `c` has no references, then `x=0`; otherwise `x` is one plus the maximum of depths of cells referred to from `c`. If `c` is a _Null_ instead of a _Cell_, returns zero.

name: EXECUTE
desc: _Calls_, or _executes_, continuation `c`.

name: JMPX
desc:
_Jumps_, or transfers control, to continuation `c`.
The remainder of the previous current continuation `cc` is discarded.

name: CALLXARGS
desc:
_Calls_ continuation `c` with `p` parameters and expecting `r` return values
`0 <= p <= 15`, `0 <= r <= 15`

name: CALLXARGS_VAR
desc: _Calls_ continuation `c` with `0 <= p <= 15` parameters, expecting an arbitrary number of return values.

name: JMPXARGS
desc: _Jumps_ to continuation `c`, passing only the top `0 <= p <= 15` values from the current stack to it (the remainder of the current stack is discarded).

name: RETARGS
desc: _Returns_ to `c0`, with `0 <= r <= 15` return values taken from the current stack.

name: RET
desc:
_Returns_ to the continuation at `c0`. The remainder of the current continuation `cc` is discarded.
Approximately equivalent to `c0 PUSHCTR` `JMPX`.

name: RETALT
desc:
_Returns_ to the continuation at `c1`.
Approximately equivalent to `c1 PUSHCTR` `JMPX`.

name: BRANCH
desc: Performs `RETTRUE` if integer `f!=0`, or `RETFALSE` if `f=0`.

name: CALLCC
desc: _Call with current continuation_, transfers control to `c`, pushing the old value of `cc` into `c`'s stack (instead of discarding it or writing it into new `c0`).

name: JMPXDATA
desc: Similar to `CALLCC`, but the remainder of the current continuation (the old value of `cc`) is converted into a _Slice_ before pushing it into the stack of `c`.

name: CALLCCARGS
desc: Similar to `CALLXARGS`, but pushes the old value of `cc` (along with the top `0 <= p <= 15` values from the original stack) into the stack of newly-invoked continuation `c`, setting `cc.nargs` to `-1 <= r <= 14`.

name: CALLXVARARGS
desc: Similar to `CALLXARGS`, but takes `-1 <= p,r <= 254` from the stack. The next three operations also take `p` and `r` from the stack, both in the range `-1...254`.

name: RETVARARGS
desc: Similar to `RETARGS`.

name: JMPXVARARGS
desc: Similar to `JMPXARGS`.

name: CALLCCVARARGS
desc: Similar to `CALLCCARGS`.

name: CALLREF
desc: Equivalent to `PUSHREFCONT` `CALLX`.

name: JMPREF
desc: Equivalent to `PUSHREFCONT` `JMPX`.

name: JMPREFDATA
desc: Equivalent to `PUSHREFCONT` `JMPXDATA`.

name: RETDATA
desc: Equivalent to `c0 PUSHCTR` `JMPXDATA`. In this way, the remainder of the current continuation is converted into a _Slice_ and returned to the caller.

name: IFRET
desc: Performs a `RET`, but only if integer `f` is non-zero. If `f` is a `NaN`, throws an integer overflow exception.

name: IFNOTRET
desc: Performs a `RET`, but only if integer `f` is zero.

name: IF
desc: Performs `EXECUTE` for `c` (i.e., _executes_ `c`), but only if integer `f` is non-zero. Otherwise simply discards both values.
Equivalent to `<{ code }> CONT` `IF`.

name: IFNOT
desc: Executes continuation `c`, but only if integer `f` is zero. Otherwise simply discards both values.
Equivalent to `<{ code }> CONT` `IFNOT`.

name: IFJMP
desc: Jumps to `c` (similarly to `JMPX`), but only if `f` is non-zero.
Equivalent to `<{ code }> CONT` `IFJMP`.

name: IFNOTJMP
desc: Jumps to `c` (similarly to `JMPX`), but only if `f` is zero.
Equivalent to `<{ code }> CONT` `IFNOTJMP`.

name: IFELSE
desc: If integer `f` is non-zero, executes `c`, otherwise executes `c'`. Equivalent to `CONDSELCHK` `EXECUTE`.
Equivalent to `<{ code1 }> CONT` `<{ code2 }> CONT` `IFELSE`.

name: IFREF
desc:
Equivalent to `PUSHREFCONT` `IF`, with the optimization that the cell reference is not actually loaded into a _Slice_ and then converted into an ordinary _Continuation_ if `f=0`.
Gas consumption of this primitive depends on whether `f=0` and whether the reference was loaded before.
Similar remarks apply other primitives that accept a continuation as a reference.

name: IFNOTREF
desc: Equivalent to `PUSHREFCONT` `IFNOT`.

name: IFJMPREF
desc: Equivalent to `PUSHREFCONT` `IFJMP`.

name: IFNOTJMPREF
desc: Equivalent to `PUSHREFCONT` `IFNOTJMP`.

name: CONDSEL
stack: f x y - x or y
desc: If integer `f` is non-zero, returns `x`, otherwise returns `y`. Notice that no type checks are performed on `x` and `y`; as such, it is more like a conditional stack operation. Roughly equivalent to `ROT` `ISZERO` `INC` `ROLLX` `NIP`.

name: CONDSELCHK
stack: f x y - x or y
desc: Same as `CONDSEL`, but first checks whether `x` and `y` have the same type.

name: IFRETALT
desc: Performs `RETALT` if integer `f!=0`.

name: IFNOTRETALT
desc: Performs `RETALT` if integer `f=0`.

name: IFREFELSE
desc: Equivalent to `PUSHREFCONT` `SWAP` `IFELSE`, with the optimization that the cell reference is not actually loaded into a _Slice_ and then converted into an ordinary _Continuation_ if `f=0`. Similar remarks apply to the next two primitives: cells are converted into continuations only when necessary.

name: IFELSEREF
desc: Equivalent to `PUSHREFCONT` `IFELSE`.

name: IFREFELSEREF
desc: Equivalent to `PUSHREFCONT` `PUSHREFCONT` `IFELSE`.

name: IFBITJMP
desc: Checks whether bit `0 <= n <= 31` is set in integer `x`, and if so, performs `JMPX` to continuation `c`. Value `x` is left in the stack.

name: IFNBITJMP
desc: Jumps to `c` if bit `0 <= n <= 31` is not set in integer `x`.

name: IFBITJMPREF
desc: Performs a `JMPREF` if bit `0 <= n <= 31` is set in integer `x`.

name: IFNBITJMPREF
desc: Performs a `JMPREF` if bit `0 <= n <= 31` is not set in integer `x`.

name: REPEAT
desc:
Executes continuation `c` `n` times, if integer `n` is non-negative. If `n>=2^31` or `n<-2^31`, generates a range check exception.
Notice that a `RET` inside the code of `c` works as a `continue`, not as a `break`. One should use either alternative (experimental) loops or alternative `RETALT` (along with a `SETEXITALT` before the loop) to `break` out of a loop.
Equivalent to `<{ code }> CONT` `REPEAT`.

name: REPEATEND
desc: Similar to `REPEAT`, but it is applied to the current continuation `cc`.

name: UNTIL
desc: Executes continuation `c`, then pops an integer `x` from the resulting stack. If `x` is zero, performs another iteration of this loop. The actual implementation of this primitive involves an extraordinary continuation `ec_until` with its arguments set to the body of the loop (continuation `c`) and the original current continuation `cc`. This extraordinary continuation is then saved into the savelist of `c` as `c.c0` and the modified `c` is then executed. The other loop primitives are implemented similarly with the aid of suitable extraordinary continuations.
Equivalent to `<{ code }> CONT` `UNTIL`.

name: UNTILEND
desc: Similar to `UNTIL`, but executes the current continuation `cc` in a loop. When the loop exit condition is satisfied, performs a `RET`.

name: WHILE
desc: Executes `c'` and pops an integer `x` from the resulting stack. If `x` is zero, exists the loop and transfers control to the original `cc`. If `x` is non-zero, executes `c`, and then begins a new iteration.
Equivalent to `<{ cond }> CONT` `<{ code }> CONT` `WHILE`.

name: WHILEEND
desc: Similar to `WHILE`, but uses the current continuation `cc` as the loop body.

name: AGAIN
desc: Similar to `REPEAT`, but executes `c` infinitely many times. A `RET` only begins a new iteration of the infinite loop, which can be exited only by an exception, or a `RETALT` (or an explicit `JMPX`).
Equivalent to `<{ code }> CONT` `AGAIN`.

name: AGAINEND
desc: Similar to `AGAIN`, but performed with respect to the current continuation `cc`.

name: REPEATBRK
desc: Similar to `REPEAT`, but also sets `c1` to the original `cc` after saving the old value of `c1` into the savelist of the original `cc`. In this way `RETALT` could be used to break out of the loop body.
Equivalent to `<{ code }> CONT` `REPEATBRK`.

name: REPEATENDBRK
desc: Similar to `REPEATEND`, but also sets `c1` to the original `c0` after saving the old value of `c1` into the savelist of the original `c0`. Equivalent to `SAMEALTSAVE` `REPEATEND`.

name: UNTILBRK
desc: Similar to `UNTIL`, but also modifies `c1` in the same way as `REPEATBRK`.
Equivalent to `<{ code }> CONT` `UNTILBRK`.

name: UNTILENDBRK
desc: Equivalent to `SAMEALTSAVE` `UNTILEND`.

name: WHILEBRK
desc: Similar to `WHILE`, but also modifies `c1` in the same way as `REPEATBRK`.
Equivalent to `<{ cond }> CONT` `<{ code }> CONT` `WHILEBRK`.

name: WHILEENDBRK
desc: Equivalent to `SAMEALTSAVE` `WHILEEND`.

name: AGAINBRK
desc: Similar to `AGAIN`, but also modifies `c1` in the same way as `REPEATBRK`.
Equivalent to `<{ code }> CONT` `AGAINBRK`.

name: AGAINENDBRK
desc: Equivalent to `SAMEALTSAVE` `AGAINEND`.

name: SETCONTARGS_N
desc: Similar to `[r] -1 SETCONTARGS`, but sets `c.nargs` to the final size of the stack of `c'` plus `n`. In other words, transforms `c` into a _closure_ or a _partially applied function_, with `0 <= n <= 14` arguments missing.

name: SETNUMARGS
desc: Sets `c.nargs` to `n` plus the current depth of `c`'s stack, where `0 <= n <= 14`. If `c.nargs` is already set to a non-negative value, does nothing.

name: SETCONTARGS
desc: Pushes `0 <= r <= 15` values `x_1...x_r` into the stack of (a copy of) the continuation `c`, starting with `x_1`. If the final depth of `c`'s stack turns out to be greater than `c.nargs`, a stack overflow exception is generated.

name: RETURNARGS
desc: Leaves only the top `0 <= p <= 15` values in the current stack (somewhat similarly to `ONLYTOPX`), with all the unused bottom values not discarded, but saved into continuation `c0` in the same way as `SETCONTARGS` does.

name: RETURNVARARGS
desc: Similar to `RETURNARGS`, but with Integer `0 <= p <= 255` taken from the stack.

name: SETCONTVARARGS
stack: x_1 x_2...x_r c r n - c'
desc: Similar to `SETCONTARGS`, but with `0 <= r <= 255` and `-1 <= n <= 255` taken from the stack.

name: SETNUMVARARGS
desc:
`-1 <= n <= 255`
If `n=-1`, this operation does nothing (`c'=c`).
Otherwise its action is similar to `[n] SETNUMARGS`, but with `n` taken from the stack.

name: BLESS
desc: Transforms a _Slice_ `s` into a simple ordinary continuation `c`, with `c.code=s` and an empty stack and savelist.

name: BLESSVARARGS
desc: Equivalent to `ROT` `BLESS` `ROTREV` `SETCONTVARARGS`.

name: BLESSARGS
desc:
`0 <= r <= 15`, `-1 <= n <= 14`
Equivalent to `BLESS` `[r] [n] SETCONTARGS`.
The value of `n` is represented inside the instruction by the 4-bit integer `n mod 16`.

name: BLESSNUMARGS
desc: Also transforms a _Slice_ `s` into a _Continuation_ `c`, but sets `c.nargs` to `0 <= n <= 14`.

name: PUSHCTR
desc: Pushes the current value of control register `c(i)`. If the control register is not supported in the current codepage, or if it does not have a value, an exception is triggered.

name: PUSHROOT
desc: Pushes the “global data root'' cell reference, thus enabling access to persistent smart-contract data.

name: POPCTR
desc: Pops a value `x` from the stack and stores it into control register `c(i)`, if supported in the current codepage. Notice that if a control register accepts only values of a specific type, a type-checking exception may occur.

name: POPROOT
desc: Sets the “global data root'' cell reference, thus allowing modification of persistent smart-contract data.

name: SETCONTCTR
desc: Stores `x` into the savelist of continuation `c` as `c(i)`, and returns the resulting continuation `c'`. Almost all operations with continuations may be expressed in terms of `SETCONTCTR`, `POPCTR`, and `PUSHCTR`.

name: SETRETCTR
desc: Equivalent to `c0 PUSHCTR` `c[i] SETCONTCTR` `c0 POPCTR`.

name: SETALTCTR
desc: Equivalent to `c1 PUSHCTR` `c[i] SETCONTCTR` `c0 POPCTR`.

name: POPSAVE
desc:
Similar to `c[i] POPCTR`, but also saves the old value of `c[i]` into continuation `c0`.
Equivalent (up to exceptions) to `c[i] SAVECTR` `c[i] POPCTR`.

name: SAVE
desc: Saves the current value of `c(i)` into the savelist of continuation `c0`. If an entry for `c[i]` is already present in the savelist of `c0`, nothing is done. Equivalent to `c[i] PUSHCTR` `c[i] SETRETCTR`.

name: SAVEALT
desc: Similar to `c[i] SAVE`, but saves the current value of `c[i]` into the savelist of `c1`, not `c0`.

name: SAVEBOTH
desc: Equivalent to `DUP` `c[i] SAVE` `c[i] SAVEALT`.

name: PUSHCTRX
desc:
Similar to `c[i] PUSHCTR`, but with `i`, `0 <= i <= 255`, taken from the stack.
Notice that this primitive is one of the few “exotic'' primitives, which are not polymorphic like stack manipulation primitives, and at the same time do not have well-defined types of parameters and return values, because the type of `x` depends on `i`.

name: POPCTRX
desc: Similar to `c[i] POPCTR`, but with `0 <= i <= 255` from the stack.

name: SETCONTCTRX
desc: Similar to `c[i] SETCONTCTR`, but with `0 <= i <= 255` from the stack.

name: COMPOS
desc: Computes the composition `compose0(c, c’)`, which has the meaning of “perform `c`, and, if successful, perform `c'`'' (if `c` is a boolean circuit) or simply “perform `c`, then `c'`''. Equivalent to `SWAP` `c0 SETCONT`.

name: COMPOSALT
desc: Computes the alternative composition `compose1(c, c’)`, which has the meaning of “perform `c`, and, if not successful, perform `c'`'' (if `c` is a boolean circuit). Equivalent to `SWAP` `c1 SETCONT`.

name: COMPOSBOTH
desc: Computes composition `compose1(compose0(c, c’), c’)`, which has the meaning of “compute boolean circuit `c`, then compute `c'`, regardless of the result of `c`''.

name: ATEXIT
desc: Sets `c0` to `compose0(c, c0)`. In other words, `c` will be executed before exiting current subroutine.
Equivalent to `<{ code }> CONT` `ATEXIT`.

name: ATEXITALT
desc: Sets `c1` to `compose1(c, c1)`. In other words, `c` will be executed before exiting current subroutine by its alternative return path.
Equivalent to `<{ code }> CONT` `ATEXITALT`.

name: SETEXITALT
desc:
Sets `c1` to `compose1(compose0(c, c0), c1)`,
In this way, a subsequent `RETALT` will first execute `c`, then transfer control to the original `c0`. This can be used, for instance, to exit from nested loops.

name: THENRET
desc: Computes `compose0(c, c0)`.

name: THENRETALT
desc: Computes `compose0(c, c1)`

name: INVERT
desc: Interchanges `c0` and `c1`.

name: BOOLEVAL
desc: Performs `cc:=compose1(compose0(c, compose0(-1 PUSHINT, cc)), compose0(0 PUSHINT, cc))`. If `c` represents a boolean circuit, the net effect is to evaluate it and push either `-1` or `0` into the stack before continuing.

name: SAMEALT
desc: Sets `c1` to `c0`. Equivalent to `c0 PUSHCTR` `c1 POPCTR`.

name: SAMEALTSAVE
desc:
Sets `c1` to `c0`, but first saves the old value of `c1` into the savelist of `c0`.
Equivalent to `c1 SAVE` `SAMEALT`.

name: CALLDICT
desc:
Calls the continuation in `c3`, pushing integer `0 <= nn <= 255` into its stack as an argument.
Approximately equivalent to `[nn] PUSHINT` `c3 PUSHCTR` `EXECUTE`.

name: CALLDICT_LONG
desc: For `0 <= n < 2^14`, an encoding of `[n] CALL` for larger values of `n`.

name: JMPDICT
desc:
Jumps to the continuation in `c3`, pushing integer `0 <= n < 2^14` as its argument.
Approximately equivalent to `n PUSHINT` `c3 PUSHCTR` `JMPX`.

name: PREPAREDICT
desc:
Equivalent to `n PUSHINT` `c3 PUSHCTR`, for `0 <= n < 2^14`.
In this way, `[n] CALL` is approximately equivalent to `[n] PREPARE` `EXECUTE`, and `[n] JMP` is approximately equivalent to `[n] PREPARE` `JMPX`.
One might use, for instance, `CALLXARGS` or `CALLCC` instead of `EXECUTE` here.
tvm_asm:
n = parse_const_u14
      => 0xF1, 0x80 | ((n / 256) as u8), ((n % 256) as u8)

name: THROW_SHORT
desc:
Throws exception `0 <= n <= 63` with parameter zero.
In other words, it transfers control to the continuation in `c2`, pushing `0` and `n` into its stack, and discarding the old stack altogether.

name: THROWIF_SHORT
desc: Throws exception `0 <= n <= 63` with  parameter zero only if integer `f!=0`.

name: THROWIFNOT_SHORT
desc: Throws exception `0 <= n <= 63` with parameter zero only if integer `f=0`.

name: THROW
desc: For `0 <= n < 2^11`, an encoding of `[n] THROW` for larger values of `n`.

name: THROWARG
desc: Throws exception `0 <= n <  2^11` with parameter `x`, by copying `x` and `n` into the stack of `c2` and transferring control to `c2`.
tvm_asm:
n = parse_const_u11
         => 0xF2, 0xC8 | ((n / 256) as u8), ((n % 256) as u8)

name: THROWIF
desc: For `0 <= n < 2^11`, an encoding of `[n] THROWIF` for larger values of `n`.

name: THROWARGIF
desc: Throws exception `0 <= nn < 2^11` with parameter `x` only if integer `f!=0`.
tvm_asm:
n = parse_const_u11
       => 0xF2, 0xD8 | ((n / 256) as u8), ((n % 256) as u8)

name: THROWIFNOT
desc: For `0 <= n < 2^11`, an encoding of `[n] THROWIFNOT` for larger values of `n`.

name: THROWARGIFNOT
desc: Throws exception `0 <= n < 2^11` with parameter `x` only if integer `f=0`.
tvm_asm: n = parse_const_u11    => 0xF2, 0xE8 | ((n / 256) as u8), ((n % 256) as u8)

name: THROWANY
desc:
Throws exception `0 <= n < 2^16` with parameter zero.
Approximately equivalent to `ZERO` `SWAP` `THROWARGANY`.

name: THROWARGANY
desc:
Throws exception `0 <= n < 2^16` with parameter `x`, transferring control to the continuation in `c2`.
Approximately equivalent to `c2 PUSHCTR` `2 JMPXARGS`.

name: THROWANYIF
desc: Throws exception `0 <= n < 2^16` with parameter zero only if `f!=0`.

name: THROWARGANYIF
desc: Throws exception `0 <= n<2^16` with parameter `x` only if `f!=0`.

name: THROWANYIFNOT
desc: Throws exception `0 <= n<2^16` with parameter zero only if `f=0`.

name: THROWARGANYIFNOT
desc: Throws exception `0 <= n<2^16` with parameter `x` only if `f=0`.

name: TRY
desc: Sets `c2` to `c'`, first saving the old value of `c2` both into the savelist of `c'` and into the savelist of the current continuation, which is stored into `c.c0` and `c'.c0`. Then runs `c` similarly to `EXECUTE`. If `c` does not throw any exceptions, the original value of `c2` is automatically restored on return from `c`. If an exception occurs, the execution is transferred to `c'`, but the original value of `c2` is restored in the process, so that `c'` can re-throw the exception by `THROWANY` if it cannot handle it by itself.
Equivalent to `<{ code1 }> CONT` `<{ code2 }> CONT` `TRY`.

name: TRYARGS
desc:
Similar to `TRY`, but with `[p] [r] CALLXARGS` internally used instead of `EXECUTE`.
In this way, all but the top `0 <= p <= 15` stack elements will be saved into current continuation's stack, and then restored upon return from either `c` or `c'`, with the top `0 <= r <= 15` values of the resulting stack of `c` or `c'` copied as return values.

name: NEWDICT
desc:
Returns a new empty dictionary.
It is an alternative mnemonics for `PUSHNULL`.

name: DICTEMPTY
desc:
Checks whether dictionary `D` is empty, and returns `-1` or `0` accordingly.
It is an alternative mnemonics for `ISNULL`.

name: STDICTS
desc:
Stores a _Slice_-represented dictionary `s` into _Builder_ `b`.
It is actually a synonym for `STSLICE`.

name: STDICT
desc:
Stores dictionary `D` into _Builder_ `b`, returing the resulting _Builder_ `b'`.
In other words, if `D` is a cell, performs `STONE` and `STREF`; if `D` is _Null_, performs `NIP` and `STZERO`; otherwise throws a type checking exception.

name: SKIPDICT
desc: Equivalent to `LDDICT` `NIP`.

name: LDDICTS
desc:
Loads (parses) a (_Slice_-represented) dictionary `s'` from _Slice_ `s`, and returns the remainder of `s` as `s''`.
This is a “split function'' for all `HashmapE(n,X)` dictionary types.

name: PLDDICTS
desc:
Preloads a (_Slice_-represented) dictionary `s'` from _Slice_ `s`.
Approximately equivalent to `LDDICTS` `DROP`.

name: LDDICT
desc: Loads (parses) a dictionary `D` from _Slice_ `s`, and returns the remainder of `s` as `s'`. May be applied to dictionaries or to values of arbitrary `(^Y)?` types.

name: PLDDICT
desc:
Preloads a dictionary `D` from _Slice_ `s`.
Approximately equivalent to `LDDICT` `DROP`.

name: LDDICTQ
desc: A quiet version of `LDDICT`.

name: PLDDICTQ
desc: A quiet version of `PLDDICT`.

name: DICTGET
desc:
Looks up key `k` (represented by a _Slice_, the first `0 <= n <= 1023` data bits of which are used as a key) in dictionary `D` of type `HashmapE(n,X)` with `n`-bit keys.
On success, returns the value found as a _Slice_ `x`.

name: DICTGETREF
desc:
Similar to `DICTGET`, but with a `LDREF` `ENDS` applied to `x` on success.
This operation is useful for dictionaries of type `HashmapE(n,^Y)`.

name: DICTIGET
desc: Similar to `DICTGET`, but with a signed (big-endian) `n`-bit _Integer_ `i` as a key. If `i` does not fit into `n` bits, returns `0`. If `i` is a `NaN`, throws an integer overflow exception.

name: DICTIGETREF
desc: Combines `DICTIGET` with `DICTGETREF`: it uses signed `n`-bit _Integer_ `i` as a key and returns a _Cell_ instead of a _Slice_ on success.

name: DICTUGET
desc: Similar to `DICTIGET`, but with _unsigned_ (big-endian) `n`-bit _Integer_ `i` used as a key.

name: DICTUGETREF
desc: Similar to `DICTIGETREF`, but with an unsigned `n`-bit _Integer_ key `i`.

name: DICTSET
desc: Sets the value associated with `n`-bit key `k` (represented by a _Slice_ as in `DICTGET`) in dictionary `D` (also represented by a _Slice_) to value `x` (again a _Slice_), and returns the resulting dictionary as `D'`.

name: DICTSETREF
desc: Similar to `DICTSET`, but with the value set to a reference to _Cell_ `c`.

name: DICTISET
desc: Similar to `DICTSET`, but with the key represented by a (big-endian) signed `n`-bit integer `i`. If `i` does not fit into `n` bits, a range check exception is generated.

name: DICTISETREF
desc: Similar to `DICTSETREF`, but with the key a signed `n`-bit integer as in `DICTISET`.

name: DICTUSET
desc: Similar to `DICTISET`, but with `i` an _unsigned_ `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTUSETREF
desc: Similar to `DICTISETREF`, but with `i` unsigned.

name: DICTSETGET
stack: x k D n - D' y -1 or D' 0
desc: Combines `DICTSET` with `DICTGET`: it sets the value corresponding to key `k` to `x`, but also returns the old value `y` associated with the key in question, if present.

name: DICTSETGETREF
stack: c k D n - D' c' -1 or D' 0
desc: Combines `DICTSETREF` with `DICTGETREF` similarly to `DICTSETGET`.

name: DICTISETGET
stack: x i D n - D' y -1 or D' 0
desc: `DICTISETGET`, but with `i` a signed `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTISETGETREF
stack: c i D n - D' c' -1 or D' 0
desc: `DICTISETGETREF`, but with `i` a signed `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTUSETGET
stack: x i D n - D' y -1 or D' 0
desc: `DICTISETGET`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTUSETGETREF
stack: c i D n - D' c' -1 or D' 0
desc: `DICTISETGETREF`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTREPLACE
stack: x k D n - D' -1 or D 0
desc: A _Replace_ operation, which is similar to `DICTSET`, but sets the value of key `k` in dictionary `D` to `x` only if the key `k` was already present in `D`.

name: DICTREPLACEREF
stack: c k D n - D' -1 or D 0
desc: A _Replace_ counterpart of `DICTSETREF`.

name: DICTIREPLACE
stack: x i D n - D' -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTREPLACE`, but with `i` a signed `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTIREPLACEREF
stack: c i D n - D' -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTREPLACEREF`, but with `i` a signed `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTUREPLACE
stack: x i D n - D' -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTREPLACE`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTUREPLACEREF
stack: c i D n - D' -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTREPLACEREF`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTREPLACEGET
stack: x k D n - D' y -1 or D 0
desc: A _Replace_ counterpart of `DICTSETGET`: on success, also returns the old value associated with the key in question.

name: DICTREPLACEGETREF
stack: c k D n - D' c' -1 or D 0
desc: A _Replace_ counterpart of `DICTSETGETREF`.

name: DICTIREPLACEGET
stack: x i D n - D' y -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTREPLACEGET`, but with `i` a signed `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTIREPLACEGETREF
stack: c i D n - D' c' -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTREPLACEGETREF`, but with `i` a signed `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTUREPLACEGET
stack: x i D n - D' y -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTREPLACEGET`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTUREPLACEGETREF
stack: c i D n - D' c' -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTREPLACEGETREF`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTADD
stack: x k D n - D' -1 or D 0
desc: An _Add_ counterpart of `DICTSET`: sets the value associated with key `k` in dictionary `D` to `x`, but only if it is not already present in `D`.

name: DICTADDREF
stack: c k D n - D' -1 or D 0
desc: An _Add_ counterpart of `DICTSETREF`.

name: DICTIADD
stack: x i D n - D' -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTADD`, but with `i` a signed `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTIADDREF
stack: c i D n - D' -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTADDREF`, but with `i` a signed `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTUADD
stack: x i D n - D' -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTADD`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTUADDREF
stack: c i D n - D' -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTADDREF`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTADDGET
stack: x k D n - D' -1 or D y 0
desc: An _Add_ counterpart of `DICTSETGET`: sets the value associated with key `k` in dictionary `D` to `x`, but only if key `k` is not already present in `D`. Otherwise, just returns the old value `y` without changing the dictionary.

name: DICTADDGETREF
stack: c k D n - D' -1 or D c' 0
desc: An _Add_ counterpart of `DICTSETGETREF`.

name: DICTIADDGET
stack: x i D n - D' -1 or D y 0
desc: `DICTADDGET`, but with `i` a signed `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTIADDGETREF
stack: c i D n - D' -1 or D c' 0
desc: `DICTADDGETREF`, but with `i` a signed `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTUADDGET
stack: x i D n - D' -1 or D y 0
desc: `DICTADDGET`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTUADDGETREF
stack: c i D n - D' -1 or D c' 0
desc: `DICTADDGETREF`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTSETGETB
stack: b k D n - D' y -1 or D' 0

name: DICTISETGETB
stack: b i D n - D' y -1 or D' 0

name: DICTUSETGETB
stack: b i D n - D' y -1 or D' 0

name: DICTREPLACEB
stack: b k D n - D' -1 or D 0

name: DICTIREPLACEB
stack: b i D n - D' -1 or D 0

name: DICTUREPLACEB
stack: b i D n - D' -1 or D 0

name: DICTREPLACEGETB
stack: b k D n - D' y -1 or D 0

name: DICTIREPLACEGETB
stack: b i D n - D' y -1 or D 0

name: DICTUREPLACEGETB
stack: b i D n - D' y -1 or D 0

name: DICTADDB
stack: b k D n - D' -1 or D 0

name: DICTIADDB
stack: b i D n - D' -1 or D 0

name: DICTUADDB
stack: b i D n - D' -1 or D 0

name: DICTADDGETB
stack: b k D n - D' -1 or D y 0

name: DICTIADDGETB
stack: b i D n - D' -1 or D y 0

name: DICTUADDGETB
stack: b i D n - D' -1 or D y 0

name: DICTDEL
stack: k D n - D' -1 or D 0
desc: Deletes `n`-bit key, represented by a _Slice_ `k`, from dictionary `D`. If the key is present, returns the modified dictionary `D'` and the success flag `-1`. Otherwise, returns the original dictionary `D` and `0`.

name: DICTIDEL
desc: A version of `DICTDEL` with the key represented by a signed `n`-bit _Integer_ `i`. If `i` does not fit into `n` bits, simply returns `D` `0` (“key not found, dictionary unmodified'').

name: DICTUDEL
desc: Similar to `DICTIDEL`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTDELGET
stack: k D n - D' x -1 or D 0
desc: Deletes `n`-bit key, represented by a _Slice_ `k`, from dictionary `D`. If the key is present, returns the modified dictionary `D'`, the original value `x` associated with the key `k` (represented by a _Slice_), and the success flag `-1`. Otherwise, returns the original dictionary `D` and `0`.

name: DICTDELGETREF
stack: k D n - D' c -1 or D 0
desc: Similar to `DICTDELGET`, but with `LDREF` `ENDS` applied to `x` on success, so that the value returned `c` is a _Cell_.

name: DICTIDELGET
stack: i D n - D' x -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTDELGET`, but with `i` a signed `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTIDELGETREF
stack: i D n - D' c -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTDELGETREF`, but with `i` a signed `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTUDELGET
stack: i D n - D' x -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTDELGET`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTUDELGETREF
stack: i D n - D' c -1 or D 0
desc: `DICTDELGETREF`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer.

name: DICTGETOPTREF
desc: A variant of `DICTGETREF` that returns _Null_ instead of the value `c^?` if the key `k` is absent from dictionary `D`.

name: DICTIGETOPTREF
desc: `DICTGETOPTREF`, but with `i` a signed `n`-bit integer. If the key `i` is out of range, also returns _Null_.

name: DICTUGETOPTREF
desc: `DICTGETOPTREF`, but with `i` an unsigned `n`-bit integer. If the key `i` is out of range, also returns _Null_.

name: DICTSETGETOPTREF
desc: A variant of both `DICTGETOPTREF` and `DICTSETGETREF` that sets the value corresponding to key `k` in dictionary `D` to `c^?` (if `c^?` is _Null_, then the key is deleted instead), and returns the old value `~c^?` (if the key `k` was absent before, returns _Null_ instead).

name: DICTISETGETOPTREF
desc: Similar to primitive `DICTSETGETOPTREF`, but using signed `n`-bit _Integer_ `i` as a key. If `i` does not fit into `n` bits, throws a range checking exception.

name: DICTUSETGETOPTREF
desc: Similar to primitive `DICTSETGETOPTREF`, but using unsigned `n`-bit _Integer_ `i` as a key.

name: PFXDICTSET
stack: x k D n - D' -1 or D 0

name: PFXDICTREPLACE
stack: x k D n - D' -1 or D 0

name: PFXDICTADD
stack: x k D n - D' -1 or D 0

name: PFXDICTDEL
stack: k D n - D' -1 or D 0

name: DICTGETNEXT
stack: k D n - x' k' -1 or 0
desc: Computes the minimal key `k'` in dictionary `D` that is lexicographically greater than `k`, and returns `k'` (represented by a _Slice_) along with associated value `x'` (also represented by a _Slice_).

name: DICTGETNEXTEQ
stack: k D n - x' k' -1 or 0
desc: Similar to `DICTGETNEXT`, but computes the minimal key `k'` that is lexicographically greater than or equal to `k`.

name: DICTGETPREV
stack: k D n - x' k' -1 or 0
desc: Similar to `DICTGETNEXT`, but computes the maximal key `k'` lexicographically smaller than `k`.

name: DICTGETPREVEQ
stack: k D n - x' k' -1 or 0
desc: Similar to `DICTGETPREV`, but computes the maximal key `k'` lexicographically smaller than or equal to `k`.

name: DICTIGETNEXT
stack: i D n - x' i' -1 or 0
desc: Similar to `DICTGETNEXT`, but interprets all keys in dictionary `D` as big-endian signed `n`-bit integers, and computes the minimal key `i'` that is larger than _Integer_ `i` (which does not necessarily fit into `n` bits).

name: DICTIGETNEXTEQ
stack: i D n - x' i' -1 or 0
desc: Similar to `DICTGETNEXTEQ`, but interprets keys as signed `n`-bit integers.

name: DICTIGETPREV
stack: i D n - x' i' -1 or 0
desc: Similar to `DICTGETPREV`, but interprets keys as signed `n`-bit integers.

name: DICTIGETPREVEQ
stack: i D n - x' i' -1 or 0
desc: Similar to `DICTGETPREVEQ`, but interprets keys as signed `n`-bit integers.

name: DICTUGETNEXT
stack: i D n - x' i' -1 or 0
desc: Similar to `DICTGETNEXT`, but interprets all keys in dictionary `D` as big-endian unsigned `n`-bit integers, and computes the minimal key `i'` that is larger than _Integer_ `i` (which does not necessarily fit into `n` bits, and is not necessarily non-negative).

name: DICTUGETNEXTEQ
stack: i D n - x' i' -1 or 0
desc: Similar to `DICTGETNEXTEQ`, but interprets keys as unsigned `n`-bit integers.

name: DICTUGETPREV
stack: i D n - x' i' -1 or 0
desc: Similar to `DICTGETPREV`, but interprets keys as unsigned `n`-bit integers.

name: DICTUGETPREVEQ
stack: i D n - x' i' -1 or 0
desc: Similar to `DICTGETPREVEQ`, but interprets keys a unsigned `n`-bit integers.

name: DICTMIN
desc: Computes the minimal key `k` (represented by a _Slice_ with `n` data bits) in dictionary `D`, and returns `k` along with the associated value `x`.

name: DICTMINREF
desc: Similar to `DICTMIN`, but returns the only reference in the value as a _Cell_ `c`.

name: DICTIMIN
desc: Similar to `DICTMIN`, but computes the minimal key `i` under the assumption that all keys are big-endian signed `n`-bit integers. Notice that the key and value returned may differ from those computed by `DICTMIN` and `DICTUMIN`.

name: DICTIMINREF
desc: Similar to `DICTIMIN`, but returns the only reference in the value.

name: DICTUMIN
desc: Similar to `DICTMIN`, but returns the key as an unsigned `n`-bit _Integer_ `i`.

name: DICTUMINREF
desc: Similar to `DICTUMIN`, but returns the only reference in the value.

name: DICTMAX
desc: Computes the maximal key `k` (represented by a _Slice_ with `n` data bits) in dictionary `D`, and returns `k` along with the associated value `x`.

name: DICTMAXREF
desc: Similar to `DICTMAX`, but returns the only reference in the value.

name: DICTIMAX
desc: Similar to `DICTMAX`, but computes the maximal key `i` under the assumption that all keys are big-endian signed `n`-bit integers. Notice that the key and value returned may differ from those computed by `DICTMAX` and `DICTUMAX`.

name: DICTIMAXREF
desc: Similar to `DICTIMAX`, but returns the only reference in the value.

name: DICTUMAX
desc: Similar to `DICTMAX`, but returns the key as an unsigned `n`-bit _Integer_ `i`.

name: DICTUMAXREF
desc: Similar to `DICTUMAX`, but returns the only reference in the value.

name: DICTREMMIN
stack: D n - D' x k -1 or D 0
desc: Computes the minimal key `k` (represented by a _Slice_ with `n` data bits) in dictionary `D`, removes `k` from the dictionary, and returns `k` along with the associated value `x` and the modified dictionary `D'`.

name: DICTREMMINREF
stack: D n - D' c k -1 or D 0
desc: Similar to `DICTREMMIN`, but returns the only reference in the value as a _Cell_ `c`.

name: DICTIREMMIN
stack: D n - D' x i -1 or D 0
desc: Similar to `DICTREMMIN`, but computes the minimal key `i` under the assumption that all keys are big-endian signed `n`-bit integers. Notice that the key and value returned may differ from those computed by `DICTREMMIN` and `DICTUREMMIN`.

name: DICTIREMMINREF
stack: D n - D' c i -1 or D 0
desc: Similar to `DICTIREMMIN`, but returns the only reference in the value.

name: DICTUREMMIN
stack: D n - D' x i -1 or D 0
desc: Similar to `DICTREMMIN`, but returns the key as an unsigned `n`-bit _Integer_ `i`.

name: DICTUREMMINREF
stack: D n - D' c i -1 or D 0
desc: Similar to `DICTUREMMIN`, but returns the only reference in the value.

name: DICTREMMAX
stack: D n - D' x k -1 or D 0
desc: Computes the maximal key `k` (represented by a _Slice_ with `n` data bits) in dictionary `D`, removes `k` from the dictionary, and returns `k` along with the associated value `x` and the modified dictionary `D'`.

name: DICTREMMAXREF
stack: D n - D' c k -1 or D 0
desc: Similar to `DICTREMMAX`, but returns the only reference in the value as a _Cell_ `c`.

name: DICTIREMMAX
stack: D n - D' x i -1 or D 0
desc: Similar to `DICTREMMAX`, but computes the minimal key `i` under the assumption that all keys are big-endian signed `n`-bit integers. Notice that the key and value returned may differ from those computed by `DICTREMMAX` and `DICTUREMMAX`.

name: DICTIREMMAXREF
stack: D n - D' c i -1 or D 0
desc: Similar to `DICTIREMMAX`, but returns the only reference in the value.

name: DICTUREMMAX
stack: D n - D' x i -1 or D 0
desc: Similar to `DICTREMMAX`, but returns the key as an unsigned `n`-bit _Integer_ `i`.

name: DICTUREMMAXREF
stack: D n - D' c i -1 or D 0
desc: Similar to `DICTUREMMAX`, but returns the only reference in the value.

name: DICTIGETJMP
desc: Similar to `DICTIGET`, but with `x` `BLESS`ed into a continuation with a subsequent `JMPX` to it on success. On failure, does nothing. This is useful for implementing `switch`/`case` constructions.

name: DICTUGETJMP
desc: Similar to `DICTIGETJMP`, but performs `DICTUGET` instead of `DICTIGET`.

name: DICTIGETEXEC
desc: Similar to `DICTIGETJMP`, but with `EXECUTE` instead of `JMPX`.

name: DICTUGETEXEC
desc: Similar to `DICTUGETJMP`, but with `EXECUTE` instead of `JMPX`.

name: DICTPUSHCONST
desc: Pushes a non-empty constant dictionary `D` (as a `Cell^?`) along with its key length `0 <= n <= 1023`, stored as a part of the instruction. The dictionary itself is created from the first of remaining references of the current continuation. In this way, the complete `DICTPUSHCONST` instruction can be obtained by first serializing `xF4A4_`, then the non-empty dictionary itself (one `1` bit and a cell reference), and then the unsigned 10-bit integer `n` (as if by a `STU 10` instruction). An empty dictionary can be pushed by a `NEWDICT` primitive instead.
tvm_asm:
n = parse_const_u10
    => 0xF4, 0xA4 | (n >> 8) as u8, n as u8

name: PFXDICTGETQ
stack: s D n - s' x s'' -1 or s 0
desc: Looks up the unique prefix of _Slice_ `s` present in the prefix code dictionary represented by `Cell^?` `D` and `0 <= n <= 1023`. If found, the prefix of `s` is returned as `s'`, and the corresponding value (also a _Slice_) as `x`. The remainder of `s` is returned as a _Slice_ `s''`. If no prefix of `s` is a key in prefix code dictionary `D`, returns the unchanged `s` and a zero flag to indicate failure.

name: PFXDICTGET
stack: s D n - s' x s''
desc: Similar to `PFXDICTGET`, but throws a cell deserialization failure exception on failure.

name: PFXDICTGETJMP
stack: s D n - s' s'' or s
desc: Similar to `PFXDICTGETQ`, but on success `BLESS`es the value `x` into a _Continuation_ and transfers control to it as if by a `JMPX`. On failure, returns `s` unchanged and continues execution.

name: PFXDICTGETEXEC
desc: Similar to `PFXDICTGETJMP`, but `EXEC`utes the continuation found instead of jumping to it. On failure, throws a cell deserialization exception.

name: PFXDICTCONSTGETJMP
desc: Combines `[n] DICTPUSHCONST` for `0 <= n <= 1023` with `PFXDICTGETJMP`.
tvm_asm:
n = parse_const_u10
   => 0xF4, 0xAC | (n >> 8) as u8, n as u8

name: DICTIGETJMPZ
stack: i D n - i or nothing
desc: A variant of `DICTIGETJMP` that returns index `i` on failure.

name: DICTUGETJMPZ
stack: i D n - i or nothing
desc: A variant of `DICTUGETJMP` that returns index `i` on failure.

name: DICTIGETEXECZ
stack: i D n - i or nothing
desc: A variant of `DICTIGETEXEC` that returns index `i` on failure.

name: DICTUGETEXECZ
stack: i D n - i or nothing
desc: A variant of `DICTUGETEXEC` that returns index `i` on failure.

name: SUBDICTGET
desc: Constructs a subdictionary consisting of all keys beginning with prefix `k` (represented by a _Slice_, the first `0 <= l <= n <= 1023` data bits of which are used as a key) of length `l` in dictionary `D` of type `HashmapE(n,X)` with `n`-bit keys. On success, returns the new subdictionary of the same type `HashmapE(n,X)` as a _Slice_ `D'`.

name: SUBDICTIGET
desc: Variant of `SUBDICTGET` with the prefix represented by a signed big-endian `l`-bit _Integer_ `x`, where necessarily `l <= 257`.

name: SUBDICTUGET
desc: Variant of `SUBDICTGET` with the prefix represented by an unsigned big-endian `l`-bit _Integer_ `x`, where necessarily `l <= 256`.

name: SUBDICTRPGET
desc: Similar to `SUBDICTGET`, but removes the common prefix `k` from all keys of the new dictionary `D'`, which becomes of type `HashmapE(n-l,X)`.

name: SUBDICTIRPGET
desc: Variant of `SUBDICTRPGET` with the prefix represented by a signed big-endian `l`-bit _Integer_ `x`, where necessarily `l <= 257`.

name: SUBDICTURPGET
desc: Variant of `SUBDICTRPGET` with the prefix represented by an unsigned big-endian `l`-bit _Integer_ `x`, where necessarily `l <= 256`.

name: ACCEPT
desc:
Sets current gas limit `g_l` to its maximal allowed value `g_m`, and resets the gas credit `g_c` to zero, decreasing the value of `g_r` by `g_c` in the process.
In other words, the current smart contract agrees to buy some gas to finish the current transaction. This action is required to process external messages, which bring no value (hence no gas) with themselves.

name: SETGASLIMIT
desc: Sets current gas limit `g_l` to the minimum of `g` and `g_m`, and resets the gas credit `g_c` to zero. If the gas consumed so far (including the present instruction) exceeds the resulting value of `g_l`, an (unhandled) out of gas exception is thrown before setting new gas limits. Notice that `SETGASLIMIT` with an argument `g >= 2^63-1` is equivalent to `ACCEPT`.

name: COMMIT
desc: Commits the current state of registers `c4` (“persistent data'') and `c5` (“actions'') so that the current execution is considered “successful'' with the saved values even if an exception is thrown later.

name: RANDU256
desc: Generates a new pseudo-random unsigned 256-bit _Integer_ `x`. The algorithm is as follows: if `r` is the old value of the random seed, considered as a 32-byte array (by constructing the big-endian representation of an unsigned 256-bit integer), then its `sha512(r)` is computed; the first 32 bytes of this hash are stored as the new value `r'` of the random seed, and the remaining 32 bytes are returned as the next random value `x`.

name: RAND
desc:
Generates a new pseudo-random integer `z` in the range `0...y-1` (or `y...-1`, if `y<0`). More precisely, an unsigned random value `x` is generated as in `RAND256U`; then `z:=floor(x*y/2^256)` is computed.
Equivalent to `RANDU256` `256 MULRSHIFT`.

name: SETRAND
desc: Sets the random seed to unsigned 256-bit _Integer_ `x`.

name: ADDRAND
desc: Mixes unsigned 256-bit _Integer_ `x` into the random seed `r` by setting the random seed to `Sha` of the concatenation of two 32-byte strings: the first with the big-endian representation of the old seed `r`, and the second with the big-endian representation of `x`.

name: GETPARAM
desc:
Returns the `i`-th parameter from the _Tuple_ provided at `c7` for `0 <= i <= 15`. Equivalent to `c7 PUSHCTR` `FIRST` `[i] INDEX`.
If one of these internal operations fails, throws an appropriate type checking or range checking exception.

name: NOW
desc:
Returns the current Unix time as an _Integer_. If it is impossible to recover the requested value starting from `c7`, throws a type checking or range checking exception as appropriate.
Equivalent to `3 GETPARAM`.

name: BLOCKLT
desc:
Returns the starting logical time of the current block.
Equivalent to `4 GETPARAM`.

name: LTIME
desc:
Returns the logical time of the current transaction.
Equivalent to `5 GETPARAM`.

name: RANDSEED
desc:
Returns the current random seed as an unsigned 256-bit _Integer_.
Equivalent to `6 GETPARAM`.
